<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Remarks</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Salix exigua </i>is a deciduous shrub or small tree usually 2-4 m tall. Plants produce an abundance of seeds, which require light for germination. Most seeds germinate within 24 hours, and those older than a week rarely germinate. Fresh alluvium deposited along rivers provides an ideal substrate for establishment. <i>S. exigua </i>sprouts from underground shoot buds, which occur on lateral roots, allowing clonal growth through vegetative reproduction called suckering. Old clones may be several meters in diameter. Regeneration may also occur through broken pieces of stems and roots. Clones sucker following fire and can rapidly re-colonize burned areas (Uchytil 1989g). Though thought a short-lived species, Vaghti (2003) reported 100-year clones along the Sacramento River. <br/>
<br/>
The alliance is widespread and common throughout California, especially along seasonally or temporarily flowing streams and at seeps. It often forms dense clonal stands, though great variation exists regionally in shrub and understory composition, ranging from Sierran mountain meadows to those in Colorado Desert oases. Plants along the Sacramento River and elsewhere in the Central Valley are the first to colonize point bars and cut banks, followed in time by <i>Populus fremontii </i>and other taller, longer-lived species (Sands 1980). Rivers with flood-control dams in place may have reduced acreage of <i>S. exigua </i>stands and attained increases in stands of longer-lived, tree willows such as <i>S. gooddingii, S. laevigata, </i>and <i>S. lucida</i>. </div>
</div>

    
	
	
