    <div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
        <h4 class="header">Regional Status</h4>
        
            <p>The range of <i>Salix exigua</i> includes the entire state.</p>
        

        <ul class="text">
        
            <li><b>Central California Coast</b> (261Aa-l). Stands are widespread along seeps, creeks, ponds, and other bodies of freshwater throughout the section. Stands are less common along the immediate coast than those of the <i>Salix lasiolepis</i> alliance.</li>
        
            <li><b>Central California Coast Ranges</b> (M262Aa-k). Stands exist at Pinnacles National Monument (Kittel et al. 2012) and are common throughout the section.</li>
        
            <li><b>Colorado Desert</b> (322Ca-c). Stands occur in Anza- Borrego Desert State Park, some adjacent to <i>Washingtonia filifera</i> alliance stands.</li>
        
            <li><b>Great Valley</b> (262Aa-z). Stands on floodplains along the Sacramento River are less than 30 to 100 years old. Woody associates include <i>Acer negundo, Arundo donax, Juglans hindsii</i> and hybrids, <i>Populus fremontii, S. lasiolepis,</i> and <i>S. melanopsis</i> (Vaghti 2003). Stands in the Sacramento-San Joaquin delta region appear common on levees, often maintained by human disturbance. They have <i>S. lasiolepis</i> commonly associated with them and are frequently tangled with briars of <i>Rubus armeniacus</i> or <i>Rosa californica</i> (Hickson and Keeler-Wolf 2007).</li>
        
            <li><b>Klamath Mountains</b> (M261Ah-i, Ar). Stands occur in the eastern subsections at lower elevations along the Trinity River.</li>
        
            <li><b>Modoc Plateau</b> (M261Gg, Go-p). Stands occur along the Pit River west of Goose Lake and in several of the lower valleys of the section.</li>
        
            <li><b>Mojave Desert</b> (322Aa-d, Af-p). Stands occur along permanent or seasonal streams, such as the Colorado and Mojave rivers, and contain <i>Populus fremontii</i> and <i>S. gooddingii</i> trees. Stands at permanent springs, as in the Saline Valley, occur with stands of the <i>Baccharis sergiloides, B. salicifolia,</i> and <i>Prosopis glandulosa</i> alliances (Evens 2000, Thomas et al. 2004).</li>
        
            <li><b>Mono</b> (341De-f, Dh-l). Stands are common east of the Sierra Nevada escarpment throughout the section.</li>
        
            <li><b>Northern California Coast</b> (263Ac, Ag, Aj, Al-m). Stands are common along creeks and rivers in the southern subsections.</li>
        
            <li><b>Northern California Coast Ranges</b> (M261Bb, Bd-f). Stands occur in the lower elevation areas of the sections.</li>
        
            <li><b>Northern California Interior Coast Ranges</b> (M261Ca-c). Stands line many of the permanent creeks in the section.</li>
        
            <li><b>Northwestern Basin and Range</b> (342Ba, Bc). Stands occur at freshwater springs and creeks in Surprise Valley and near Honey Lake.</li>
        
            <li><b>Sierra Nevada</b> (M261Er-t). Stands along the eastern slope, including Lee Vining Canyon (Keeler-Wolf et al. 2003b) are nearly pure <i>S. exigua</i> with dense understory cover of grasses and sedges. Other stands contain <i>Rosa woodsii</i> and <i>S. lutea,</i> as at Convict Lake and west of Walker Pass.</li>
        
            <li><b>Sierra Nevada Foothills</b> (M261Fa-e). Stands occur along creeks and rivers and line ponds and reservoirs in all the subsections (Klein et al. 2007, Potter 2005).</li>
        
            <li><b>Sonoran Desert</b> (322Ba-e). Stands are extensive along the Colorado River and occur at many springs throughout the section.</li>
        
            <li><b>Southeastern Great Basin</b> (341Fa-f). Stands are common at springs and in well watered canyons below about 1800 m throughout the section.</li>
        
            <li><b>Southern California Coast</b> (261Ba-j). Stands are widespread along creeks, channels, rivers, flood basins, and other water-storage areas in the section.</li>
        
            <li><b>Southern California Mountains and Valleys</b> (M262Ba-d, Bf-g, Bi-l, Bn, Bp). Stands exist along some of the major seasonal streams, including those of the eastern Los Angeles Basin, the Santa Margarita River, and streams bordering the Colorado Desert (Keeler-Wolf et al. 1998).</li>
        
            <li><b>Southern Cascades</b> (M261Db-c, Dh, Dj). Stands occur in the lower elevation subsections.</li>
        
        </ul>
    </div>


    
	
<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Management Considerations</h4>
	<div class="text"> Because the alliance is so widespread, it is an integral part of riparian systems throughout most of the state. Its colonizing and stabilizing characteristics make it an important member in the riparian disturbance cycle, and reduced flooding regularity has diminished its representation along some streams. </div>
</div>

    

    

